page 1 -----------------------------------------------------
                       QUICK START

For the those adventurous souls who shun documentation, and want to
lunge blindly into their brand-new software, we present the 
ZOETROE Quick Start.  ZOETROE has far too many functions to 
learn in a coule of pages.  But we can give you a taste of its power.

The following instructions assume you've used plenty of Amiga
software and know what terms lick click, double-click, and drag mean.
We assume you've used menu bars, and you know what to do when you
see: "Choose Fill from the Draw menu."  But if you get lost, don't
worry about it.  ZOETROPE can be learned quickly and enjoyably by 
sitting down with the program and working your way through the
tutorials following this section.  You can always come back and visit
later on.

Decided to try this anyway?  Okay, make copies of both ZOETROPE
disks.  Now, place disk A (the main disk) in your drive, open its
window, and double-click on the ZOETROPE icon.  When the blank
screen comes up, replace ZOETROPE disk A with ZOETROPE disk B
(the data disk).

PREPARATION
Before plunging into the unknown, it's always a good idea to plan a
path of retreat.

The right mouse button (or [space bar]), will back up from where you
are.  It will also toggle between the full screen and the menu display.
You can only draw on the ZOETROPE screen when there are no menus
displayed.  If you try something and it doesn't work, click the right
mouse button and try it again.  If it still doesn't work - read the
documentation.
page 2 ------------------------------------------------

note: In the following Quick Start section, we won't tell you to 
right-click to exit the menus.  But if you have to be somewhere else
on screen, you may have to leave the menu you're in to get there.

* Exit ZOETROPE by selecting Quit from the Menu drop-down
* The [Help] key will undo mistakes
* If you get lost, here's how to clean up and return to default settings:

CLEAN-UP
1.  Select Kill Seq from Menu, and click on Yes.
2.  Select Time from Menu, click on To Frame, make sure Tween is
     highlighted.
3.  Select APM f/x from Menu, select Clear, click on Yes.
4.  Select Color f/x from Color, drag the line beneath the color squares
     so that it spans all the colors, click on (and highlight) f/x and
     Normal, then select Render.
5.  Select Load/Save from Menu, click on and highlight Normal and .rif.
6.  Deselect Ping ong in Modes menu (no asterick).

You could also accomplish all of the above by exiting to the
Workbench then restarting the program.  But then you would never
learn.

Again, the following instructions are bare-bone and assume you know
how to select an item from the menu bar, how to exit a submenu, and
how to activate the full screen when you want to draw (all done with 
the right mouse button).

TEXT & APM
You've just booted.  A blank screen with a cross-shape cursor appears.
* Select Set Font from Menu
* Click to select a nice fat font from the window. (Drag the slider bar
   at the left to view more fonts).
* Select Text from Draw Menu.
* Select red color from Color menu.
* From full screen, left-click to set cursor somewhere left of center.
* Type your name on screen (first name will do).
* Right click to exit text mode.
* Select a contrasting color from the Color menu.
* Select Pixel f/x from Menu.
* Select Edge In, the click on the black background.
* Select Clip from Clip menu.
* Select Clear ic from Frame menu.
page 3 -------------------------------------------------------

* Press [Return] twice (creates 21 frames).
* Select APM f/x from Menu.
* Click on lower-case 'f' at right until it is a red, lower-case 'a' (To All
   frames).
* Adjust the full Turns slide bar (the lower one) to read l.
* Click on Center, then Default.
* Click on Axis, drag the top bar to the right (100), second bar to the
   left (-100), third bar to the right (100).
* Click on Preview.
* Select Size and Scale, drag Enlarge bar to 50 (Scale reads 2.00).
* Click on Preview.
* Select Path, click on Samle Path, drag a squiggly line on screen.
   (Release button to comlete ath).
* Click on review.  Reeat Path, above, until you like it.
* Select Render, answer Yes (or press [Y]).
* Select ing Pong from Modes menu.
* Press [F8] to play the animation.

PIXEL F/X
* Use Clean Up sequence, above, to return ot default settings.
* Select Load/Save from menu.
* Click on Load, select the FOREMAN.RIF file from selector box.
* After the file loads, return to full screen, and press [F8] to play.
* Select Time from Menu, click and highlight To All.
* Select the green color from the Color menu (first column, second
   from bottom).
* Select ixel f/x from Menu, select Edge In, left-click in black
   background, answer Yes.
* Play animation: [F8].
* From Pixel f/x menu, select Outline, answer Yes, play animation.
* From Pixel f/x menu, select Rile.  Drag box 20 by 20 ppixels
   (ignore numbers in aprentheses), release button, answer yes, play
   animation.
* From ixel f/x menu, select Tile.  Drag the box around the man's
   head, answer Yes, play animation.
* Select Time from Menu, click and highlight To Frame. Press [F10]
   to move to last frame (#12).
* Select color f/x from Color menu. Drag both ends of the line under
   the color bars to encompass all colors.  Select Chrone, click on
   Render.
* Click on Fade, and highlight Blend.  Click on lower-case 'f' until it
   is a red 'a' (To All Frames).
* Click on Render, answer Yes, play animation.
page 4 ------------------------------------------------------

CRYSTALIZE
* Use Clean Up sequence to return to default settings.
* Press [Return] four times (41 frames).
* Turn off Filled in Modes menu (no asterick).
* Select color # 16 from Color menu (fifth down in the first column).
* Select Box in the Draw menu and draw a three-inch box in center of
   screen.
* Select color # 31 from Color menu (lower-right).
* Select the second brush on the top row of the Brush menu.
* Select Draw in Draw menu.  Click once in the center of the box to
   place a brush-shaped dot.
* Select Time from Menu, click to highlight To All.
* Select Pixel f/x from Menu, select Crystalize, answer Yes.
* Select Ping Pong in Modes menu.  Play the animation.

NOTE: One-megabyte machines may run out of memory using 
certain procedures.  Try booting your system with no disk in the 
external drive.  See Appendix A for memory saving tips.
