page 7 ------------------------------------------------

The ZOETROPE manual is divided into two main sections: Tutorial
and Reference.  The several tutorials in the first section provide hands-
on introductions to ZOETROPE's features; the Reference Section 
contains all ZOETROPE features organized by screen-menu location for
easy look-up.  At the end of the manual are several appendices covering 
miscellaneous information.

BEFORE YOU BEGIN, BACK UP YOUR DISKS!  Both ZOETROPE
disks may be copied using the disk copy procedure described in your
Amiga owner's manual.  Please back them up and store the originals in
a safe place.  Throughout the manual, when we refer to the 
ZOETROPE disks, we willbe referring to the back-up copies.

There may be one or more files on your disks titled README.  These
contain important information you should read before running any
program.

Your ZOETROPE package should contain two disks: ZOETROPE
Main (disk A), and ZOETROPE Data (disk B).

ZOETROPE Main contains the ZOETROPE program itself which is
the only file needed to operate ZOETROPE.  The remaining files and
directories contain utilities and fonts.  Any operable programs besides
ZOETROPE are described in the appendices at the end of this manual.

ZOETROPE Data (disk B) contains the data files used by the
ZOETROPE tutorial section plua additional graphics demos.

You may move all files from both disks into a hard disk if you have
one.  During the tutorials, we will refer to the disk containing the
tutorial files as the ZOETROPE data disk, or disk B.
page 8---------------------------------------------------

While your'e copying disks, we suggest formatting a couple of disks to
store your animation sequences.

Now, place your copy of ZOETROE in whichever drive you wish to 
run it from, open that drive's window, and double-click on the
ZOETROPE icon.

NOTE: ZOETROPE requires a minimum of one-megabyte of RAM,
and oerates in the Amiga low-resolution graphics mode.  If you
have a one-megabyte system, we recomend booting your system
without the external drive to save memory.
page 9 -------------------------------------------------------------
              ZOETROPE TUTORIAL I: AN OVERVIEW

ZOETROPE is many programs in one, but it is essentially an
animation program.  It is also a delta-file editor, as well as a paint
program.  It's closest relatives may be found among the high-end
grahpics workstations that create many of the titling animations you
see on such programs as the TV news, or sports programs.  Depending
on what you want to ut into it, ZEOTROPE can be powerful,
complex, or very simple.  It's also a lot of fun.

This first tutorial will quickly introduce the heart of the ZOETROPE
system without getting bogged down in a lot of details.  The succeeding
tutorials are designed to lead you through every feature of ZOETROPE
until you feel comfortable and familiar with its functions.

NOTE:  The following section assumes a cleared ZOETROPE
system.  If you're coming here directly from the Quick Start section,
above, use the Clean-Up procedure, or reboot ZOETROPE.

GETTING THE BASICS OUT OF THE WAY

When you first enter ZOETROPE, a blank screen appears.  Move the
mouse and a hollow, white cross appears as your mouse cursor.

MOUSE RULES:
* The right mouse button is used to escape from where you are.
* The left mouse butotn is used for all else.

Naturally, there is an excetion to the first rule: The right mouse
button is also used to access the top menu bar.  Hold down the right
mouse button to display the menu bar, then run it over the various
titles to dislay their menus.  While still holding down the button,
place the cursor over the item you wish (a red box will outline it), then

page 10 -------------------------------------------------------------

release the right mouse button to select that item.  If you move the
mouse pointer away from the menu before releasing the button, no
action will be taken.

In this manual, when you see a hrase like "Select Circle from the
Draw menu", it means to use the above procedure to find the item 
labeled "Circle" in the menu titled "Draw", and select it by releasing the
right mouse button while "Circle" is outlined.

NOTE:  The letters you see to the right of the menu selections are
keyboard alternatives.  These can speed things considerablyonce
you get used to ZOETROPE, but to begin with, the handiest
keyboard alternatives are [Space Bar]=right mouse button,
[Help]=Undo, and [Esc]=Clear Pic.

Examples of Mouse Rule # 1: Click the right mouse button and a bar
appears at the bottom of the screen (the Playback Bar).  Right-click
again to 'escape' from this bar.  Using the procedure described above,
select Load/Save from the Menu.  After the Load/Save menu appears,
press the right mouse button to 'escape' from the Load/Save menu.

An example of Mouse Rule # 2:  Select Circle from the Draw menu,
place your mouse cursor in the center of the screen, hold down the left
mouse button, and move the mouse away from the center to create a
circle.  Release the button to leave the circle.  Select Undo from the
Frame menu to undo the circle. (Try drawing the circle with the
Playback Bar displayed.  Doesn't work.  Remember: You can only 
draw on a full screen with no menus displayed.
page 11 -------------------------------------
                   PLAYING AN ANIMATION

ZOETROPE animation files are called 'rif' files, after the rif delta file
format developed by author Jim Kent.  Select Load/Save from Menu.
There are five file types, indicated by their extender names, which are
directly accessible by ZOETROPE.  When you first access the 
Load/Save menu, the .rif extender is already highlighted.  To load a rif
file, click on Load.

NOTE:  Special file conversion utilities are included on your
ZOETROPE disk to convert animation files from other pgorams to
the rif format.  See Appendix C for details.

The ZOETROPE file selector appears, displaying a list of rif files from 
whichever disk or drawer you booted ZOETROPE.  We want to load an
animation called DINO.RIF, which is on Disk B of your ZOETROPE
disks.  If you have two disk drives and have placed Disk B in DF1:,
click in the DF1: box of the file selector to display the files on that
drive.  If youhave one disk drive, replace ZOETROPE Disk A with
ZOETROPE Disk B, then click on DF0: to relist the files on the new
disk. (Hard disk owners: the names of your first five hard disk
partitions will also appear in buttons on your file selector).

You can scoll u and down the list of files by clicking on the arrows
to the left of the file window, or by dragging the slider bar.  DINO.RIF
page 12 -------------------------------------

will be found inthe drawer labeled TUTORIALS.  Click on the drawer
name in the file window to list the files inside.

To load DINO.RIF, either left-clickon the file name then click on OK,
or double-click onthe file name.  An arrogant dragon will appear,
strolling in the center of your screen.  (Dino is a character from an
animation by Doug Thomas).  The animation will appear jerky because
ZOETROPE is displaying each frame as it is loaded from the disk.

Once the load is comleted, click the right mouse button to remove the
Load/Save menu.  You should now have a dragon on your screen, and
the Playback Bar at the bottom. (If the Playback Bar is not there, right-
click to make it appear).

The Playback Bar works a lot like a VCR controller.  right now, your
ZOETROPE screen is displaying frame # 1 (indicated by the slider bar),
out of a total of eight frames of naimation (as shown at the right of the
Playback Bar).  To play the DINO animation, click on the plain, right-
facing arrow (three boxes to the right of the slider bar).  Right-click to
halt the animation.

Select zoom in the Modes menu, place the box over the dragon and
left-click.  Now lay the animation.  Select Zoom again to return to a
normal screen.

You can try out all the other icons in the layback Bar but, for now, 
avoid clicking on the total-frames number (8), the 'f' to its right, and
the two 'non-arrow' icons that are two boxes to the right and to the left
of the slider bar.  If you accidentally click on these, you can restore the
original animation by simple reloading it.  But go ahead and try out the
other buttons.  They're all logical enough.  You can also move
anywhere in the animation by clicking within the slider bar, or dragging
the frame number in the slider bar.

Now let's try the boxes we avoided. (If you've already clicked on them
and altered the animation, now's the time to reload the original
DINO.RIF.

Move to frame # 5 of the animation, then click on the icon that's two
boxes ot the right of the slider bar.  The slider number becomes a six,
and the total frames number increases to nine.  The icon you just
page 13 ------------------------------------- 

clicked on inserts one copy of the displayed frame at that position in the
animation, and moves the slider bar to the right one frame.  Frames # 5
and # 6 are now idential copies.  Play back the animation and note the
hesitation caused by the duplicate frames.

To get rid of the extra frame, move to frame #6 or #6, select Delete
from the Frame menu, and click on Yes.  The duplicate frame is
removed, and the animation is back ot a smooth eight frames.

The icon two boxes left of the slider barr performs the identical function,
except that the slider bar moves to the left of the inserted frame.

How's your animation?  Still looking good?  If not, reload the original
DINO.RIF before continuing.

AUTOMATIC ANIMATION

Many of ZOETROPE's functions may be applied differently over
a range of frames to automaticallyi create animation effects.

Move to frame #1 and select Cut from the Clip menu.  Move the cross
hairs that appear just above and to the left of Dino, then drag the mouse 
(hold down the left moust button) to create a box around the dinosaur
before releasing the button.  The box disappears, but you've captured
the image in the ZOETROPE clip buffer.

Select Paste from the Clip menu and drag Dino to the upper left of the
screen before releasing the button to paste him there.  Take a look at
some of the other frames to see that he's only been pasted to frame #1.

Now we'll do some Time Painting.  Select Time from the Menu.
Click on To All to highlight it, then right-click to return to whichever
frame you're on (it doesn't matter). Notice that the small 'f' in the
Playback Bar has been replaced by a while 'a' against a red background.
page 14-----------

Again, select Paste from the Clip menu.  This time, drag Dino to the
lower right of the screen before releasing the button.  A requestor asks if
you want to do this to all frames.  Sure, why not.  Click on Yes.
When ZOETROPE finishes pasting to all frames, play the animation.

Select Time again from the menu, and click on Tween to turn off the
tweening function.  Exit the Time menu, select Paste from the Clip
menu, drag Dino to the lower left, and answer Yes to the prompt.  Play
the animation.

Return to the Time menu, turn Tween back on (highlighted), then
select To Segment.  In the box below To Segment, drag the dot to the
right until it becomes a bar (the Segment Range Bar).  Drag the end of
the bar until the number to its right indicates frame #6.  Drag the other
end of the bar until its number (the one to the left) indicates frame #3.
Drag-Paste Dino one more time, then play the animation.

Notice that while in To Segment mode (note the 's' in the Playback
Bar), ZOETROPE plays only the segment of frames indicated by the
Segment Range Bar.  The frame mode must be in either To Frame or
To All for full playback of all frames.  Stop the pplayback and click on
the 's' to change the frame mode To All (each click on the frame-mode
box cycles the mode through 'f', 's', and 'a').  Now, when the entire 
animation is played, you can see that the newly pasted image appears
only through frames #3-#6.

Let's get rid ofthe clutter.  Click on the frame mode letter ('a') to set it
To Frame ('f').  Select Kill Seq from the Menu and answer 'Yes' to
clear all frames from memory.  The Playback Bar shows you have a
single frame.  Click once on the frame-total number in the Playback
Bar to append ten duplicate frames to your animation (in this case, a
total of 11 blank frames).  This is a shortcut method of adding extra
frames.  Whenever you click on the total frames number (or press
[Return] ten additional frames will be added to the end of the
animation.

You've erased the Dino animation, but your clip buffer still contains
his image. Select Move from the Clip menu, move Dino to the middle
of the screen and release the button.  Move works just like Paste -
except that it doesn't paste.  It simply moves the clip image to another
location.  Move is also handy for viewing the contents of your clip
buffer.  It's also a good way to try out the different ways of dragging an
image around.  Go ahead and move Dino around the screen.  Notice that

page 15--------------------------------------ZOETROPE TUTORIAL I: AN OVERVIEW

you can place the mouse pointer anywhere on screen to begin the drag
move - you can even move Dino completely off the screen!  (Don't
forget where you ut him.)  When you're through, move him back to
center screen.

Set the frame mode To All and select Rotate from the Clip menu.
Place the cursor just outside thelower-right corner of the clip box, hold
down the left button, and drag in a counter-clockwise direction about
180 degrees.  Release the left mouse button, then right-click, answer
Yes to the prompt, and play the animation.

Again, select Rotate from the Clip menu.  Place the pointer inside the
clip box and drag Dino to the lower left corner of the screen.  Place the
pointer just outside the right side of the clip box and drag it
counterclockwise to about 180 degrees before releasing it.  Note that at
this point, you may still drag the clip image from inside its box, or try
a slightly different rotation.  When you're ready, right-click, then play
back the animation.

Many of the clip functions vary, depending on where you place the
mouse pointer in relation to the clip box.  These are all described in
detail in the following tutorials, and in the Reference section.

Choose Stretch from the Clip menu, place the pointer inside the clip
box and drag Dino to the upper center of the screen.  Place the pointer
outside the right side of the clip box and drag the box to the right to
stretch the image.  Right click, answer affirmative, then watch the
animation.

Select ing Pong from the Modes menu and play the animation again.

DOIN' THE APM

As we have demonstrated, by using the Clip functions over a range of
frames, you can rotate, stretch, and move (using Paste) your images.
With the APM f/x menu, you can combine these operations - and
more.

Move Dino to the upper left corner of the screen, then select APM f/x
from the Menu.  First we'll try a rotation.  At boot-up, 'Turn' and
'Turns' are already highlighted in the APM menu. (If they're not, click 
on Turn, then on Turns.)  To the right of Turns are two slider bars.
page 16------------------------------------ZOETROPE TUTORIAL I: AN OVERVIEW

The top slider adjusts partial turns (+-360 degrees), and the bottom
adjusts full turns +-16).

Adjust the lower bar for one full turn, counter-clockwise (positive
number) by clicking on arrow to its right.  Now, click on the box
labeled Preview to see the effect.  (You may click on Preview as many
times as you wish, it has no effect on your animation).

During the review, the white cross on the screen indicates the center of
rotation.  To move it, click on Center, then select Mouse XY and move
the crosshairs to the lower-right corner of the clip box (approximately).
Left-click to set the center, then click on Preview to view the results.

Now, click on Default and preview the results.  Default automatically
places the cross in the center of the clip box.

The clip box has been rotating about the Z axis. (The Z axis is the
depth axis running through the screen from your eyes.  The X axis is a
horizontal line parallel to the screen, and the Y axis is a vertical line.)
Click on Axis, then click on X and preview the turn.  Click on Y and
preview the turn.

The three slider bars above X,Y, and Z represent the placement of
(from top to bottom) the X, Y, and Z axes.  Drag the upper slider bar
all the way to the left (-100), leave the middle slider bar at 100, and drag
the lower slider bar all the way to the left (-100).  Click on preview.

Now that we have an interesting rotation, let's add movement across the
screen.  There are two ways to move an image from the APM.  We'll
use Path for this example.  Click on Path, then click on Sampled Path.
Point at Dino, hold down the left mouse button and drag a looping path
that ends near the lower-right of the screen.  Preview the result.  (You
can keep redoing the path until it moves the way you want it).
page 17------------------------------------ZOETROPE TUTORIAL I: AN OVERVIEW

Now we'll add scaling to our rotating, moving image.  Select Size and
drag the lower bar (labeled Enlarge) until it reads approximately 50, and
the percentage under Scale reads about 2.00.  (Exact values are not 
always possible, depending on the size of clip buffer.)  Click on 
Preview.
Finally, click on Render, then click on Yes.  ZOETROPE will take 
care of the rest.  When the rendering is complete, play back the results.

This is the basic process of the APM.  Up until the time you select
Render, you may continue to adjust any of the APM functions,
repreviewing until you get what you like.

PUT IT ALL TOGETHER

Now that we've done some animation doodling, let's see if we can put
some of these features to use.  What if we wanted Dino to walk across
the screen?

Select Kill Seq from the Menu, answer Yes, then select Load/Save from
the menu and reload the original DINO.RIF animation.

Return to the APM f/x menu and click on Preview.  All our original
settings are still there, and the clib box floats across the screen.  Up
until now, we've moved a clip image all over the screen, but it hasn't
been animated.  Now, we want Dino to walk across the screen.  In the
lower-left corner of the APM f/x menu is the word Clip.  Click on it to
toggle it to Seq.  Now, the APM settings will affect the entire 
animation sequence.

Click on Preview.  Oops, we don't want Dino flying all over!   Click on
Clear and answer Yes to the prompt.  The Clear button erases, or
zeroes, all previous APM settings. (But don't worry, you can save your
APM settings to disk from the Load/Save menu.)

Dino is going to walk from the left side of the screen to half way off
the right.  To place him at his starting position, click on Move (the
Move in the APM menu!) and select Mouse XY.  Drag Dino (and the
entire screen) all the way to the left until his tail is about one-half inch
away from the left edge of the screen.  Note the coordinates at the top of
the screen.  The dy coordinate stands for 'delta y', or the change from
the original Y coordinate position.  Make sure this reads zero before
you release the mouse button.  When the APM menu returns, note the
page 18-----------------------------------ZOETROPE TUTORIAL I: AN OVERVIEW

values in the slider bars.  The top bar (X position)reflects the change
on the X axis (about -100).  The Y and Z bars should both read zero.  If
you accidentally joggled the mouse before releasing it, you can adjust the
Y axis to zero in the slider bar.

Click on Preview.  The entire screen glides to the left.  Hmmmm...
Looks like this won't work, he'll be walking backwards.  Click on the
't' (tween) to turn it off, and try review again.  That's better.  Withot
tween, only the final position of the sequence (or clip) is pasted
identially to each frame.  Click on Render and check out the results.
Dino should now be walking at the left of the screen.

Now, let's walk Dino across the screen.  Click on Move in the APM
menu and drag Dino to the right until he's halfway off the screen (and
the Y delta remains at dy()).  This should be approximately dx256.
Click on Preview - oops, forgot to turn the tween back on.  Click on
't' to highlight tween, then preview again.  The sequence box should
glide across the screen.  Go ahead and render it.

Turn off the Ping Pong in the Modes smenu before playing the animation.
Not bad!  All we need now is a background.

Select Load/Save from the Menu.  We want to load a background
picture, so select .pic as the type of file.  If we loaded a picture with the
settings as they are, it would replace the frame in memory. (Actually, 
it would replace all frames since the frame mode is set To All.)  For our
example, though, we want a background under Dino.  So, click on
Under.

NOTE:  File merges using Under and Over begin loading at
the frame currently displayed.  In the following examples, make
sure you are at frame #1 before loading Under or Over.

Now, click on Load.  Since you're in To All mode, any kind of file I/O
is irreversable and a prompt will warn you.  Answer Yes.  The file
selector will now display only those files with a .pic extender.  (If you
want to display all files, click on the word Wildcard.  To return to the 
.pic extender, click on Wildcard again.)  Select and load the file labeled
DINO.PIC.  Your background picture will be loaded into each frame
behind the Dino animation.
page 19-----------------------------------ZOETROPE TUTORIAL I: AN OVERVIEW

Play the animation.  Looks pretty good, but let's add one more touch.
It's just as easy to merge (or 'composite') animations as it is to
composite pictures.  Reenter the Load/Save menu, select .rif, then click
on Over.  Now, click on Load and select the file DINOTITLE.RIF.

When the first frame of the animation appears, it will wait for you to
position it.  If you liked where it was, you could simply click the right
mouse button.  This animation is a credit title which might look better
at the bottom of the screen, so drag it to the lower ortion of the screen
before releasing the button.  Answer yes to the rompt and, when the
loading is comleted, play your comleted animation.

It's easy to save your comleted dnimation (and it's a good idea to save
many interim animations before activating irreversable functions.  Place
a blank, formatted disk in whichever drive is available.  If you have a 
single drive, replace ZOETROPE disk B with the formatted disk.

NOTE:  No disk formatted?  Select Pause from the Menu to return 
to the Workbench.

Select Load/Save, make sure .rif is highlighted (we want to save the
animation, not just a single frame picture.)  During a Save operation,
the Normal, Over, Under, and Splice modes don't matter, but make sure
the frame mode is set either To All, or To Frame.

Click on Save.  Point to the box to right of the word 'File:' and click
to get a square cursor.  Type in a file name, such as: DINOALL.RIF,
and press [Return].  ZOETROPE will display each frame of the
animation as it saves it to disk.

MOVING ON

Before you move on, play around with what you have already learned.
Experiment and try new combinations.  This tutorial has been only an
introduction to ZOETROPE.  Whole menus - such as ixel f/x and
Color f/x - have not even been mentioned.

The remaining tutorials use a more methodical approach, taking you
step-by-step through all of ZOETROPS's functions:

TUTORIAL II: DRAWING, will show you how to use ZOETROPE's paint-
rogram features - the backbone of the program.
