page i -----------------------------------APPENDIX A - MEMORY CONSERVATION

ZOETROPE can store u pto 4096 frmes in RAM memory, with pixel-
level accuracy and real-time playback - all through the magic of a delta
compression scheme which only stores the differences between frames.

Normally, delta compression lets you work on much longer animations
than if you were using a 'page flipper' package where each frame would
take up 40K.  But in the worst case (digitized data is particularly bad)
Zoetrope will also take 40K per frame.  Sooner or later, (sooner if your
Amiga has one-megabyte of RAM) you will see an 'Out of Memory'
alert.  The easiest, but most expensive, solution is to buy more
memory for your Amiga. But here are a few tips that will help you get
the most out of the memory you already have:

1.  Avoid detailed scrolling backwards.
2.  When possible, use color registers #1, #2, #4, #8, or #16 for any
    moving images.
3.  Never use a 'Separate' or 'Fill' action where you could get the
    same effect by changing the color palette.
4.  Remember that color palette and color effects are the least memory
    intensive type of animation.
5.  With digitized data a 'defocus all' followed by an 'apm seq reduce
    50% no tween' often roduces vidio appearing to have all the detail
    of the original, but using 1/4 of the memory.
6.  Moving parts made up of a solid color take up less memory than
    moving patterns.
7.  Moving parts using only color registers #0, #1, #2, and #3 will
    only take up 40% of the space of moving parts using color register
    #31 (if they're both moving over a color 0 background).
page ii -----------------------------------APPENDIX A - MEMORY CONSERVATION

Once you have run out of memory, the best thing to do is save your
animation in two or more pieces via 'save segment', and work on the
ieces separately.  Sometimes this is inconvenient, or you're working
on a file too large to fit into memory to begin with.  For this urose
there's a 'Patch' option in the Load/Save menu.  Large files may be
loaded a piece at a time via Patch.  You may even edit a patch in the
middle of a file and save it back out, or age through a file.  Unless
your disks are faster than mine, though, you'll want to work on files
that fit in RAM whenever possible.
page iii ----------------------------------APPENDIX B - ZOEPLAY & QUICKRIF

ZOEPLAY and QUICKRIF are dislay programs for .rif file animations.
Both these programs may be freely distributed to friends and user groups,
and uploaded or downloaded via BBS or commercial online services.  However,
Jim Kent owns the copywright on both programs - they are NOT in the
public domain, and they are NOT to be sold.

ZOEPLAY
ZOEPLAY is the easiest to use of the two animation display programs.
After double-clicking on its icon, a blank screen, cursor, and abbreviated
PlayBack Bar will appear.  Hold down the right mouse button to display
the 'Zoeplay' menu.

Select Load to load any .rif file, using the ZOETROPE file selector.
The animation will be loaded into memory and each frame displayed
during the load.

Select Play to play the animation.  Hold down the left mouse button to
speed up the playback.  Press the right mouse button, or any key, to
halt the playback.

The Status display shows the total number of frames in memory, and
the current memory usage.  CHIP free is the total bytes available in
CHIP memory, followed by the largest contiguous block of CHIP
memory.  FAST free is the total bytes available of FAST memory,
followed by the largest contiguous block of FAST memory.

Select Speed to adjust the playback rate with the slider bar.
page iv ----------------------------------APPENDIX B - ZOEPLAY & QUICKRIF

Select ing ong to activate ping-pong playback mode.  An asterisk
will appear next to the menu selection signifying that Ping-Pong is
active.

Select Quit to return to the workbench.

The Playback Bar at the bottom of the screen works the same way as
the main ZOETROPE Playback Bar, except there are no frame creation
icons.  Fromleft to right are: fast-reverse, reverse, move one frame left,
frame slider bar, move one frame right, forward, and fast forward.

QUICKRIF
QUICKRIF is a short program designed to be run from within the Amiga CLI.
As a result, it has no file icon, but can be found by typing DIR from
the CLI prompt.  It is most useful for making self-running demos, but
some knowledge of the CLI is necessary to successfully operate the program.

QUICKRIF uses a different and much denser memory delta scheme than
ZOEPLAY and ZOETROPE.  Animations will load much faster, but they
may not replay as smoothly.  You tend to get a jerk as things loop
from the last to the first frame in particular.

The following commands may be entered directly at the CLI prompt, or
they may be added to your s:Startup-Sequence file for auto-booting.
(See your Amiga User's Manual for details on creating Startup-Sequence
'execute' files).

To play once forward through an animation file called, say
MyCartoon.rif, type:

	quickrif MyCartoon.rif

To play the same file 100 times

	quickrif 100 MyCartoon.rif

To play multiple files sequentially

	quickrif 1 title.rif 10 demo.rif 1 credits.rif

(Plays title.rif once, then demo.rif 10 times, then credits.rif once)
page v  ----------------------------------APPENDIX B - ZOEPLAY & QUICKRIF

To play multiple files alternatively

	quickrif 5 a.rif + b.rif + c.rif

(Loads a.rif, b.rif and c.rif into memory, and plays them, spliced
together, five times).

QUICKRIF has been included primarily as an example for programmers,
its source code is available on the ZOETROPE disk.  See the RIF
section of the following appendix for details.
page vii ---------------------------APPENDIX C - FILE FORMATS & CONVERSIONS

Zoetrope uses five different types of files directly, and several others
may be converted to ZOETROPE format with the utility programs on the
ZOETROPE disk.

The directly accessible ZOETROPE file tyes include the main animation
file, .rif, which is used to store complete video sequences.
ZOETROPE can also use single-frame IFF picture files, and brush (.win)
and color (.col) files.  There's also a file type (.apm) for saving
the settings of the APM f/x menu.

Using the two file utilities on your ZOETROPE disk, you may convert
Aegis Animator .script files, Videoscape 3D and Video Titler .anim
files, CYBER PAINT (Atari ST) .SEQ files, and non-320x200 .rif
files (from Live!) into 320x200 .rif files.

NOTE:  More file formats may be added at a later date.  Look for any 
README files on your ZOETROPE disks for the latest update information.

ANITOZOE
ANTIOZOE converts Aegis Animator .script files to ZOETROPE .rif
files.  Double click on the ANITOZOE icon. When the blank screen
appears, hold down the right mouse button to dislay the menu bar,
labelled 'AntiToZoe'.  While still pressing the right button, point to
AntiToZoe to dislay the menu.  Select Load Script, then select the
Aegis Animator script file that you wish converted.
page viii ---------------------------APPENDIX C - FILE FORMATS & CONVERSIONS

The first frame of the animation will be displayed.  At this point, you
may immediately create a .rif file by selecting Save Rif, entering a new
filename in the file selector, and clicking on OK.

WARNING:  If you are using one disk drive, your disk must have enough
room for both the original as well as the new animation file.
No matter how many drives you se, YOU MUST LEAVE THE
DISKS IN THE DRIVE DURING THE CONVERSION.  You must also leave the
disks in the drive during playback (see below).

Once the initial frame of an animation is displayed,the following
options are available:

You may play the animation in a continuous loop by selecting Play
from the menu.  Halt the animation at any point by pressing any key or
button.

Select Time to alter either the playback speed of the script animation or
of the resultant .rif animation.  Two slider bars will appear.  The upper
bar, labeled 'Ani Speed', alters the speed of the script file playback,
based on the Aegis Animator system (the higher the number, the faster
the rate).  This adjustment will noticeably change the playback within
ANITOZOE.

The lower slider sets the ZOETROPE rate at which the .rif file will be
saved (the higher the number, the slower the rate).  This adjustment
will not be noceable during playback from within ANITOZOE, but
will affect the smoothness of the animation (and the total number of
frames used) from within ZOETROPE. Thus, a very slow Ani Speed
combined with a very fast Zoe Speed creates the smoothest possible
animation in ZOETROPE, but uses the greatest number of frames.

The Status display shows current memory usage.  CHIP free is the total
bytes available in CHIP memory, followed by largest contiguous
block of CHIP memory.  FAST free is the total bytes available of
FAST memory, followed by the largest contiguous block of FAST
memory.

Select Quit to return to the Workbench.
page ix ---------------------------APPENDIX C - FILE FORMATS & CONVERSIONS

CROPPER
CROPPER converts ANIM (VideoScape 3D, Video Titler) files,
CYBER PAINT (Atari ST) .SEQ files, and non-320x200 .rif files
(from Live!) into 320x200 .rif files.  It can also save out .rif files as
ANIM or Aegis Animator .script files.

To operate CROPPER, double-click on the CROPPER icon.  Hold
down the right mouse button to dislay the two menus: File and Crop.
Select Load from the file menu, then select the file you wish to
convert.  This may be any of the file types mentioned above; CROPPER
will automatically identify the chosen file type.

The first frame of the animation will be displayed.  At this point, you
may immediately convert the file by selecting Save Rif, Save Anim, or
Save Script in the File menu, entering a new filename in the file
selector, and clicking on OK.

WARNING:  If you are using one disk drive, your disk must have enough
room for both the original as well as the new animation file.
No matter how many drives you se, YOU MUST LEAVE THE
DISKS IN THE DRIVE DURING THE CONVERSION.  You must also leave the
disks in the drive during playback (see below).

Once the initial frame of an animation is displayed, the following
options are available:

You may move to the next frame of the animation by selecting Next
Frame from the File menu.

You may play the animation by selecting Play from the File menu.
Playback will be jerky and somewhat slow since each frame of the
animation is loaded from disk.  You may halt the animationat any 
point by pressing any key or button.

If you are converting an anim file that is a resolution other than
320x200, the entire screen will not be visible on your monitor, and the
aspect ratio (X to Y ratio) may be wrong.  You may use the options in
the Crop menu to correct this.

Select Center to center an oversized animation within the 'window' of
your monitor screen.  Select Upper Left to place the monitor 'window'
at the upper left corner of an oversized animation.  Or, you may select
Mouse Move, and drag the animation to any position.
page x ---------------------------APPENDIX C - FILE FORMATS & CONVERSIONS

Select Half Width to shrink the width of an oversized animation to fit
within the width of the monitor display.  Select Half Height to shrink
the Height of an oversized animation to fit within the height of the
monitor display.

The Status display shows current memory usage.  CHIP free is the total
bytes available in CHIP memory, followed by largest contiguous
block of CHIP memory.  FAST free is the total bytes available of
FAST memory, followed by the largest contiguous block of FAST
memory.

Select Quit to return to the Workbench.

RIF FILES
The following is a brief description of the .rif file format.  For 
programmers, source code in C nad assembler, to read and play .rif files,
is provided on your ZOETROPE disk in Quickrif.arc.  This is the full
source to the quickrif utility compressed with the arc program (arc is
avilable at most Amig users groups, bulletin boards, and many Amiga
dealers).

Rif files are a highly compressed form of picture storage capable of real-
time forward-only decompression.  (Since ZOETROPE needs to ping-pong
it stores pictures in RAM differently).  Rif files are used by the
Live! real time video digitizer as well.

ZOETROPE rif files are composed of three parts.  First there is a 64-
byte header starting with the ASCII letters RIFF.  This structure
contains the seed, length of file, frame count, and other useful bits.  A
C declaration of the structure is in vcomp.h.  The second part is a list
of offsets to each frame from the beginning of the file.  The last part is
composed of the frames themselves.  Each frame has a 56 byte header,
64 bytes of color map, followed by the compressed pixel imagery one
bit-plane at a time.

The first frame of a .rif is compressed using a vertical byte-run-length
compression scheme.  This, typically, is 30% smaller than the IFF
ILBM horizontal byte-run-length scheme.  Subsequent frames are also
vertically run-length encoded, but runs which are the same from frame
to frame are skipped entirely.  The interesting source code for this is in
unvscomp.asm.

		            Finally, The End...

                            Typed in by EAST COAST
                            for M.A.A.D.
